{
  "text": "Investigators in two studies suggested that listeners may hear the geometric mean, rather than the arithmetic mean, as the perceived center of vibrato tones, particularly with large vibrato widths (S. [CITATION_1] Shonle & Horan, 1980) . Comparison of arithmetic and geometric means of the performed tones in this study indicated little difference between the two (as might be expected with vibrato widths of 20 to 36 cents): Geometric means were less than 1 cent below the arithmetic mean for all violin and cello tones. One could argue, and be technically correct, that because several of the perception means were 1 to 2 cents below the (arithmetic) mean of the vibrato tones, then those values correspond more closely to the geometric mean. However, a difference as small as 1 to 2 cents would have little practical consequence for musicians in a performance context [CITATION_2] .",
